04956nam a22004815i 9780804765206DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047652067 a10.1515/97808047652062doi  a(DE-B1597)582599  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0080002bisacsh1 aMacauley, Melissa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSocial Power and Legal Culture :bLitigation Masters in Late Imperial China /cMelissa Macauley. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (436 p.) :b3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw, Society, and Culture in China00tFrontmatter -- tLaw, Society, and Culture in China -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tTables -- tChronology of Chinese Dynasties and Qing Reigns -- tINTRODUCTION Legal Culture and Historical Change -- tCHAPTER ONE The Evolution of a Crime and Its Punishments -- tCHAPTER TWO Statecraft Legalism and Administrative Despair -- tCHAPTER THREE Mechanics of Litigation Mastery: Who, Where, How -- tCHAPTER FOUR A Clientele Empowered -- tCHAPTER FIVE The Disputation of the Body Snatchers: Judicial Depravity and Legal Culture -- tCHAPTER SIX Entrepreneurs of Power: Land, Lineage, and Litigation Mastery on the Southeast Coast -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Trickster Tales: Cunning Power and the Invocation of an Alternative Male Ideal -- tCONCLUSION "Lawyer" Bashing and Litigation Loathing -- tAPPENDIX Ruminations on Statistics for Litigation Rates in the Eighteenth Century -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tCharacter List -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAsserting that litigation in late imperial China was a form of documentary warfare, this book offers a social analysis of the men who composed legal documents for commoners and elites alike. Litigation masters—a broad category of legal facilitators ranging from professional plaintmasters to simple but literate men to whom people turned for assistance—emerge in this study as central players in many of the most scandalous cases in eighteenth- and nineteenth-century China. These cases reveal the power of scandal to shape entire categories of law in the popular and official imaginations. The author characterizes litigation masters as entrepreneurs of power, intermediaries who typically emerge in the process of limited state expansion to provide links between local interests and the infrastructure of the state. These powermongers routinely acted in the interests of the local elite and the male lineage. But cases preserved in criminal archives also reveal a clientele surprisingly composed of the subordinate actors in legal disputes—widows fighting in-laws and other men, debtors contesting creditors, younger brothers disputing older ones, and common people charging the rich. Challenging earlier scholarship claiming that the Chinese legal system simply maintained the hegemony of elites and the patriarchal order, this study shows how the legal tools of domination were often transformed into weapons of social resistance and revenge. The book also examines the manifold ways in which legal practice, Confucian ideology, and popular entertainments like opera and storytelling coalesced into Chinese legal culture. Popular traditions in particular did not simply reflect legal culture but actively influenced it, shaping common presumptions about law that transcended differences of class and region. Exploring Chinese legal culture in the structural contexts of commercialization, changes in property transactions, and ineradicable litigation backlogs, the author explains why litigation was condemned by all classes of Chinese men and women even as all classes litigated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory -- World. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aBernhardt, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuang, Philip C. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476520640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804765206423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804765206/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles